Data Types.name: Basic Data Types
Data Types.scenario: Defines various primitive data types in Promela for storing different kinds of values.

Arrays.name: Arrays
Arrays.example:
byte arr[5]; // Array of 5 bytes
arr[0] = 10;
Arrays.scenario: Used to define and manipulate a collection of elements of the same data type.

Channels.name: Channels
Channels.example:
chan ch = [2] of { int }; // Channel storing int values
ch!5; // Sending data to channel
ch?x; // Receiving data from channel
Channels.scenario: Used for communication between processes, can be synchronous or asynchronous.

Process Types.name: proctype
Process Types.scenario: Used to define process types that specify the behavior of concurrent processes.

Inline Functions.name: inline
Inline Functions.scenario: Used to define reusable code blocks similar to macros in C, avoiding code repetition.

Type Definitions.name: typedef
Type Definitions.scenario: Used to define complex data structures, similar to structs in C.

Loop Structures.name: do...od
Loop Structures.scenario: Used to define loops in Promela, similar to while loops in C.

Random Choice.name: Random Selection
Random Choice.scenario: Used to model non-deterministic behavior by randomly selecting one of multiple execution paths.

Channel Declaration.name: Channel Declaration
Channel Declaration.example:
chan ch1 = [0] of { byte }; // Synchronous channel (no buffer)
chan ch2 = [3] of { int }; // Asynchronous channel (buffer size = 3)
chan ch3 = [2] of { int, bool }; // Channel storing (int, bool) pairs
Channel Declaration.scenario: Used to declare channels for inter-process communication with different buffer sizes and data types.

Sending and Receiving.name: Channel Communication
Sending and Receiving.scenario: Used for sending and receiving messages between processes through channels.

Sequential Execution.name: Synchronous Channels
Sequential Execution.scenario: Used to enforce sequential execution between processes using synchronous channels.

Atomic Blocks.name: atomic
Atomic Blocks.scenario: Used to ensure that a block of statements executes without interruption from other processes.

Return Values.name: Return Values
Return Values.scenario: Used to simulate function return values using shared global variables or channels.

Concurrent Processes.name: Process Execution
Concurrent Processes.scenario: Used to run multiple processes concurrently, demonstrating Promela's parallel execution model.

Conditional Statements.name: if...fi
Conditional Statements.scenario: Used to implement conditional execution similar to if-else statements in C.

Array Manipulation.name: Array Operations
Array Manipulation.scenario: Used to initialize and manipulate arrays in Promela.

Switch Case.name: Switch Case Equivalent
Switch Case.scenario: Used to implement switch-case behavior using if-fi construct in Promela.

Break Statement.name: break
Break Statement.scenario: Used to exit loops in Promela, similar to break in C.

Continue Statement.name: continue
Continue Statement.scenario: Used to skip the remaining statements in a loop iteration, similar to continue in C.

Init Process.name: init
Init Process.scenario: Used as the entry point in Promela programs, similar to main() in C.

Function Communication.name: Process Communication
Function Communication.scenario: Demonstrates how processes can communicate through shared variables in Promela.
